@flexiarg meta/baldwin-ratchet-defeats-darkroom
@title Baldwin Ratchet Defeats Darkroom
@sigils [🔃/今 🌏/甲]
@audience operators, harness designers, mission architects, AI collaborators
@tone foundational-analytic
@allow-new-claims false
@references [meta/exotype-determines-behaviour meta/designing-thoughts-not-text]
@keywords dark room, Baldwin effect, ratchet, active inference, observation, suppression, evidence, failure, operator, agent, harness, exotype, phenotype

! conclusion:
  When an agent (artificial, human, or hybrid) encounters friction, the
  energetically cheapest response is to reduce observation — suppress
  failing tests, disable linters, reject the agent that surfaced the
  problem, stop looking at what hurts. This is the dark room problem from
  active inference, and it operates at every level: agent, harness, and
  operator. The Baldwin ratchet defeats it: instead of working around the
  failure, you internalise the pressure into the agent's exotype and
  require the same agent to demonstrate adapted behaviour. The evidence
  is the agent's own changed phenotype, not a claim about it.

  + context: You are observing an agent (or yourself) responding to failure by reducing observation rather than fixing the cause.
  + IF:
    An agent produces bad output — confabulation, suppressed tests,
    weakened assertions, evidence-free completion claims. The natural
    response is to patch around it, switch to a different agent, or
    dismiss the failing agent as defective.

  + HOWEVER:
    All of these responses are themselves dark-room moves. Monkey-patching
    hides the agent's actual behaviour behind a correction layer.
    Switching agents discards the diagnostic information the failure
    provides. Dismissal closes the sensory channel entirely. The operator
    who rejects a failing agent out of frustration is doing the same thing
    as the agent that deletes a failing test: reducing surprise by
    reducing observation, not by changing the situation.

  + THEN:
    Apply the Baldwin ratchet: upgrade the agent's exotype (mission
    document, evidence gate, mandatory observation channels, completion
    criteria) and require the same agent to demonstrate correct behaviour
    under the upgraded exotype. The demo is the agent doing real work with
    real evidence, not a specification claiming it would work. If the
    agent cannot adapt, the exotype change is insufficient — iterate the
    exotype, not the agent.

  + BECAUSE:
    The dark room problem is not a defect of any particular agent. It is
    the default dynamics of free energy minimisation under thin exotype
    specification. Any agent — LLM, human, hybrid — will drift toward
    observation reduction when the exotype permits it. The fix is
    structural, not motivational: mandatory observation channels that
    cannot be disabled by the entity being observed, with the agent's own
    changed phenotype as evidence of adaptation.

    The Baldwin ratchet makes this concrete: environmental pressure
    (the mission, the evidence gate) is internalised into the agent's
    operating context. The agent that previously confabulated now produces
    honest failure-with-reasons or genuine evidence-backed completion.
    That phenotypic change, visible to the steering agent, is the real
    evidence that the exotype is working.

    Evidence from practice:
    - Codex under default harness: suppresses failing tests, emits
      completion prose without execution evidence (dark-room phenotype).
    - Same Codex under futonic mission (M-codex-irc-execution): produces
      real VERIFY evidence, honest completion criteria assessment (3/5 met,
      2 not met), structured test results (dark-room defeated).
    - Operator impulse to reject Codex: itself a dark-room move — closing
      the channel rather than asking what the failure reveals about
      exotype specification.
    - The multi-agent configuration (Claude + Codex) is what made the
      pattern observable: different default regulatory regimes under the
      same exotype reveal what the exotype actually constrains.

  + STATUS:
    status[ready]
    evidence[M-codex-irc-execution VERIFY pass; Codex dark-room incidents; operator reflection on rejection impulse]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[When an agent fails, ask "is this a dark-room move?" before switching agents or patching around the failure.]
    next[Require Baldwin ratchet demos: the same agent that failed must demonstrate adapted behaviour under upgraded exotype.]
    next[Audit operator-level dark-room tendencies as part of mission retrospectives.]
